on System of the USSR and Russia|Master of Sports]] in [[Taekwondo]]<ref name=UFCprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Valentina-Shevchenko|title=Valentina Shevchenko - Official UFC Fighter Profile|website=UFC.com|accessdate=March 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314103844/http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Valentina-Shevchenko|archive-date=March 14, 2016}}</ref> <br> [[Unified Sports Classification System of the USSR and Russia|International  Master of Sports]] in [[Muay Thai]]<ref name=UFCprofile /> <br> [[Unified Sports Classification System of the USSR and Russia|Master of Sports]] in [[Boxing]]<ref name=UFCprofile /> <br> [[Unified Sports Classification System of the USSR and Russia|Master of Sports]] in [[Kickboxing]]<ref name=UFCprofile /> <br> Black belt<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2016/7/19/12207172/fighter-on-fighter-breaking-down-ufc-on-fox-20-valentina-shevchenko-chicago-mma |title=Fighter on Fighter: Breaking down UFC on FOX 20's Valentina Shevchenko |website=MMAmania.com |date= July 20, 2016|accessdate=July 26, 2016}}</ref> and [[Unified Sports Classification System of the USSR and Russia|Master of Sports]] in [[Judo]]<ref name=UFCprofile />\n| years_active    = 2000\u2013present<ref name=\"marca.com\">{{cite web|url= http://www.marca.com/2010/01/15/mas_deportes/otros_deportes/1263554162.html|publisher= [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |title=  No hay quien tumbe a 'La Bala' Shevchenko |language=Russian, English, Spanish |accessdate=December 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n| box_win         = 2\n| box_kowin       = \n| box_loss        = 0\n| kickbox_win     = 57\n| kickbox_kowin    = 4\n| kickbox_loss     = 2\n| mma_kowin        = 6\n| mma_subwin       = 7\n| mma_decwin       = 6\n| mma_koloss       = 1\n| mma_subloss      = \n| mma_decloss      = 2\n| relatives       = [[Antonina Shevchenko]] (sister)\n| university      = University of Arts Kyrgyzstan<ref name=UFCprofile />\n| school          = \n| url             = \n| boxrec          = 534197\n| sherdog         = 45384\n| footnotes       = \n| updated         = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Women\u2019s [[Muay Thai]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flag|Kyrgyzstan}} }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flag|Peru}}       }} \n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Combat Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2010 World Combat Games|2010 Beijing]] | -60 kg}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2013 World Combat Games|2013 Saint Petersburg]] | [[Muay Thai at the 2013 World Combat Games|-60 kg]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Valentina Anatolievna Shevchenko''' (va-len-tyna ; Russian:\u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0428\u0435\u0432\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e; born {{Birth date|1988|3|7}}) is a [[Kyrgyz people|Kyrgyzstani]]-born [[Peruvians|Peruvian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufcespanol.com/news/valentina-shevchenko-historia-de-kirguistan-peru|title=Valentina Shevchenko, Historia De Kirguist\u00e1n A Per\u00fa|website=UFC|language=es|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref> professional mixed martial artist and former Muay Thai fighter. She competes in the [[Flyweight (MMA)|women's flyweight]] division of the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC), where she is the current [[UFC Women's Flyweight Championship|Women's Flyweight champion]]. Shevchenko became champion at [[UFC 231]] after defeating [[Joanna J\u0119drzejczyk]], whom she also previously defeated three times in amateur Muay Thai bouts. Shevchenko is widely considered one of the best female fighters in the world. As of March 9, 2020, she is ranked #3 in [[List of current UFC fighters#Rankings|UFC women's pound-for-pound rankings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/rankings|title=Rankings {{!}} UFC|website=www.ufc.com|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShevchenko was born in Frunze, Kirghizia, USSR on March 7, 1988, into a Russian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmaboxing.ru/news/news-mma/Valentina-Shevchenko-Konechno-ya-russkaya-39641.html|title=\u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0428\u0435\u0432\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e: \"\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0447\u043d\u043e, \u044f \u2013 \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f.\"|date=September 10, 2018|website=mmaboxing.ru|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> family with [[Soviet Union|Soviet]], and later [[Kyrgyzstan]]i, citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sovsport.ru/mma/articles/1072794-valentina-shevchenko-moja-istorija-s-nunies-ne-zakonchena|title= Valentina Shevchenko: \"My history with Nunes is not finished\"|publisher=sovsport.ru|accessdate=September 8, 2018}}</ref> After becoming interested in combat sports at an early age, she began Taekwondo at age 5, under the influence of her older sister [[Antonina Shevchenko|Antonina]] and her mother, who had practiced the sport.<ref name=\"wordpress1\">{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://wombatsports.wordpress.com/2015/02/10/valentina-shevchenko-talks-cross-sport-success-signing-to-legacy-mma/|title= Valentina Shevchenko Talks Cross Sport Success; Signing to Legacy MMA|publisher= Wombat Sports|date= February 10, 2015|accessdate=February 10, 2015}}</ref> At age 12 she branched out into Muay Thai kickboxing and then freestyle Vale Tudo. Her kickboxing career began in 2000 when, also at age 12, she knocked out a 22-year-old opponent, earning her the moniker \"Bullet\" from her trainer Pavel Fedotov because of her speed in the ring.<ref name=\"marca.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wban.org/biog/vshevchenko.htm|title=Women's Boxing: Valentina Shevchenko Biography|publisher=Wban.org|accessdate=December 12, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129213507/http://www.wban.org/biog/vshevchenko.htm|archive-date=January 29, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Edwards |first=Lance |url=http://www.legacyfights.net/legacy-fighting-championship-39-valentina-shevchenko/ |title=Legacy Fighting Championship 39 \u2013 Valentina Shevchenko |website=Legacyfights.net |date= |accessdate=December 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShevchenko earned an undergraduate degree in Film Directing from the University of Arts Kyrgyzstan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Valentina-Shevchenko |title=Valentina Shevchenko |publisher=UFC |date=June 8, 2019 |accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Muay Thai and kickboxing==\n[[File:Valentina Shevchenko 2014.jpg|thumb|left|Valentina Shevchenko in China, 2014]]\nFrom 2003 to 2015, Shevchenko collectively won more than 50 amateur/pro matches in K-1, Muay Thai and kickboxing (five were won by technical knockout, three were won by knockout). She received her first loss in kickboxing when she fought Debby Urkens (WFCA) in 2008 and her second one against Wang Cong (aka Cong Wang) in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valentina Schevchenko|url=https://www.awakeningfighters.com/athletes/valentina-shevchenko/|website=Awakening Fighters}}</ref> Shevchenko won 8 gold medals (2003, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2012, 2014) when she competed in the IFMA world championships, as well as the IMFA Royal World Cup in 2015. During these competitions, Shevchenko defeated future [[UFC Women's Strawweight Championship|UFC Women's Strawweight Champion]] [[Joanna J\u0119drzejczyk]] three times and future UFC fighter [[Lina L\u00e4nsberg]] once. Shevchenko is considered to be one of the best female Muay Thai fighters in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valentina \"Bullet\" Shevchenko the Pride of Muaythai|url=http://www.wmcmuaythai.org/2014/06/05/valentina-bullet-shevchenko-the-pride-of-muaythai|website=World Muaytahi Council|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Valentina Shevchenko - Hall of Fame|url=http://www.lamaimuaythaicamp.com/news/valentina-shevchenko-hall-of-fame/|website=Lamai muaythai Camp}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n\n===Early career===\nShevchenko has competed in mixed martial arts since 2003, compiling a record of 19-3.\n\n===Legacy Fighting Championship===\nIn 2014, it was announced that Legacy FC had signed Shevchenko for MMA and kickboxing.<ref>{{cite news|title= Legacy FC adds pro kickboxing to its resume for January debut on AXS TV|publisher= MMA Junkie|date=|url= http://mmajunkie.com/2014/09/legacy-fc-adds-pro-kickboxing-to-its-resume-for-january-debut-on-axs-tv|accessdate=October 27, 2014}}</ref> She faced [[Jan Finney]] on February 27, 2015, at [[Legacy Fighting Championship|Legacy Fighting Championship 39]], winning the fight via unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2015/12/16/10295880/ufc-signs-womens-bantamweight-valentina-shevchenko-kaufman-fight-fox-17-mma-news |title=Welcome to the UFC, Valentina Shevchenko |publisher=Bloody Elbow |date= December 16, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nShevchenko made her UFC debut as a short-notice replacement for [[Germaine de Randamie]] against [[Sarah Kaufman (fighter)|Sarah Kaufman]] at [[UFC on Fox 17]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ufc.com/news/de-Randamie-out--Shevchenko-to-debut-against-Kaufman|title=de Randamie out, Shevchenko to debut against Kaufman|publisher=UFC.com|author=|date=December 11, 2015|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> She won the fight via split decision (28\u201329, 29\u201328, and 29\u201328).<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Damon |url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ufc-valentina-shevchenko-upsets-sarah-kaufman-in-ufc-debut-121915 |title=Valentina Shevchenko upsets Sarah Kaufman in UFC debut |publisher=FOX Sports |date=December 16, 2015 |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn her second fight for the promotion, Shevchenko faced [[Amanda Nunes]] at [[UFC 196]] on March 5, 2016. Although she made an impressive and strong performance in the third round, her slow start in the first two gave the rounds to Nunes. She lost the fight by unanimous decision (29\u201328, 29\u201327, and 29\u201327).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/03/ufc-196-results-amanda-nunes-outlasts-valentina-shevchenko-for-decision-win|title=UFC 196 results: Amanda Nunes outlasts Valentina Shevchenko for decision win|date=March 6, 2016|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=July 19, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn her third UFC fight, Shevchenko faced former [[UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship|UFC Women's Bantamweight Champion]] [[Holly Holm]] at [[UFC on Fox: Holm vs. Shevchenko]] on July 23, 2016. After losing the first round, she rallied back to take over the fight and won a dominant unanimous decision (49\u201346, 49\u201346, and 49\u201346).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com.au/mma/story/_/id/17132150/valentina-shevchenko-upsets-holly-holm-decision|title=Shevchenko upsets Holm by decision|work=ESPN.com|access-date=July 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShevchenko faced [[Julianna Pe\u00f1a]] in a possible title eliminator match in the main event at [[UFC on Fox: Shevchenko vs. Pe\u00f1a]] on January 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2016/12/06/julianna-pena-valentina-shevchenko-ufc-denver/|title=Julianna Pena vs. Valentina Shevchenko to headline \"UFC on Fox\" card at Denver|date=December 6, 2016|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=December 12, 2018}}</ref> She won the fight by armbar submission in the second round. The win also earned Shevchenko her first ''Performance of the Night'' bonus.<ref name=Pena>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/01/ufc-on-fox-23-bonuses-valentina-shevchenko-jorge-masvidal-among-50000-extra-winners|title=UFC on FOX 23 bonuses: Valentina Shevchenko, Jorge Masvidal among $50,000 extra winners|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=January 28, 2017|accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====UFC Bantamweight title fight====\n\nShevchenko was expected to rematch the current women's bantamweight champion Amanda Nunes on July 8, 2017, at [[UFC 213]], but on the day of the fight Nunes fell ill and pulled out of the fight. The doctors cleared Nunes to fight, but she didn't feel up to it, so the fight was called off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Shevchenko-Expects-Totally-Different-Fight-in-Future-Rematch-vs-UFC-Champ-Nunes-116623|title=Shevchenko Expects 'Totally Different Fight' in Future Rematch vs. UFC Champ Nunes|last=Sherdog.com|website=Sherdog|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref> Joanna J\u0119drzejczyk offered to replace Nunes, but the Nevada State Athletic Commission could not clear her on such short notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/07/joanna-jedrzejczyk-valentina-shevchenko-amanda-nunes-ufc-213-nsac-dana-white|title=Why couldn't Joanna Jedrzejczyk fight last minute at UFC 213? 'It was about a pregnancy test'|date=July 9, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe rematch against Nunes was rescheduled to [[UFC 215]] on September 9, 2017, in [[Edmonton, Alberta]]. After a very close back-and-forth fight, Shevchenko lost the fight via split decision. In the post-fight press conference, she voiced her disagreement with the judges' decision but also said she respected the outcome.<ref>{{Citation|last=MMAFightingonSBN|title=UFC 215: Valentina Shevchenko Post-Fight Press Conference \u2013 MMA Fighting|date=September 9, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QkJ0D67YWQs|accessdate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Out of 22 media outlets, 10 scored it for Nunes, 10 for Shevchenko, and 2 scored it a draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmadecisions.com/decision/8400/Amanda-Nunes-vs-Valentina-Shevchenko|title=Amanda Nunes def. Valentina Shevchenko :: UFC 215 :: MMA Decisions|website=www.mmadecisions.com}}</ref>\n\n====Flyweight division====\nIn September 2017, Shevchenko revealed plans to join the 125-pound [[flyweight]] division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightful.com/report-valentina-shevchenko-considering-move-flyweight|title=Report: Valentina Shevchenko Considering A Move To Flyweight {{!}} Fightful MMA|website=www.fightful.com|language=en|access-date=September 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShevchenko faced promotional newcomer [[Priscila Cachoeira]] on February 3, 2018, at [[UFC Fight Night 125]]. She won the fight in an extremely dominant fashion and via rear-naked choke in round two, outstriking her opponent 230-3. This win earned her the [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]] bonus.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2018/02/ufc-fight-night-125-bonuses-valentina-shevchenkos-domination-among-nights-winners|title=UFC Fight Night 125 bonuses: Valentina Shevchenko's domination among night's winners|date=February 4, 2018|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=February 4, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShevchenko was scheduled to face champion [[Nicco Monta\u00f1o]] on September 8, 2018, at [[UFC 228]]. However, prior to the weigh-ins for the event, Montano was transported to a hospital due to the effects of weight cutting. The bout was cancelled and Montano was stripped of the Women's Flyweight title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/9/7/17833436/dana-white-says-nicco-montano-is-no-longer-the-ufc-womens-flyweight-champion|title=Dana White says Nicco Monta\u00f1o is no longer the UFC women's flyweight champion|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref> UFC officials then announced that Shevchenko would fight for the vacant 125-pound flyweight title later in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/09/nicco-montano-stripped-ufc-title-valentina-shevchenko-fight-vacant-belt-ufc-228|title=Nicco Montano stripped of UFC title; Valentina Shevchenko to fight for vacant belt|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=September 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== UFC Women's Flyweight Championship ====\nOn September 20, 2018, it was announced that Shevchenko would face [[Joanna J\u0119drzejczyk]], who was returning to [[Flyweight (MMA)|Flyweight]], on December 8, 2018, at [[UFC 231]] for the vacant [[UFC Women's Flyweight Championship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/mma/news/joanna-jedrzejczyk-vs-valentina-shevchenko-set-for-flyweight-title-fight-at-ufc-231/|title=Joanna Jedrzejczyk vs. Valentina Shevchenko set for flyweight title fight at UFC 231|author=Brandon Wise|date=September 20, 2018|access-date=September 21, 2018|publisher=cbssports.com}}</ref> Due to [[UFC 230]] being in need of a main event, Shevchenko was booked against [[Sijara Eubanks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/mma/news/joanna-jedrzejczyk-vs-valentina-shevchenko-set-for-flyweight-title-fight-at-ufc-231/|title=Joanna Jedrzejczyk vs. Valentina Shevchenko set for flyweight title fight at UFC 231|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=October 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Eubanks was expected to face [[Jessica Eye]] at [[UFC 232]], before being moved to face Shevchenko.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmaonpoint.com/news/2018/8/31/jessica-eye-vs-sijara-eubanks-targeted-for-ufc-232|title=Jessica Eye vs. Sijara Eubanks Targeted for UFC 232|work=MMA On Point|access-date=October 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> After the UFC announced a [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|Heavyweight Championship]] bout between [[Daniel Cormier]] and [[Derrick Lewis (fighter)|Derrick Lewis]] to serve as the main event of [[UFC 230]], UFC confirmed the bout between Shevchenko and Eubanks was canceled and that Shevchenko would return to her original bout at [[UFC 231]] against J\u0119drzejczyk.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/24943833/daniel-cormier-derrick-lewis-headline-ufc-230|title=Cormier-Lewis official as UFC 230 main event|work=ESPN.com|access-date=October 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Shevchenko defeated J\u0119drzejczyk by unanimous decision to become the new [[UFC Women's Flyweight Championship|UFC Women's Flyweight Champion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/12/twitter-reacts-valentina-shevchenko-title-victory-joanna-jedrzejczyk-ufc-231|title=Twitter reacts to Valentina Shevchenko's title victory over Joanna Jedrzejczyk at UFC 231|date=December 9, 2018|website=MMAjunkie|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the first defense of her UFC flyweight title, Shevchenko faced [[Jessica Eye]] in the co-main event at [[UFC 238]] on June 8, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaweekly.com/valentina-shevchenko-makes-first-flyweight-title-defense-at-ufc-238-in-chicago/|title=Valentina Shevchenko makes first flyweight title defense at UFC 238 in Chicago|publisher=MMAWeekly.com|author=Ken Pishna|date=March 11, 2018|access-date=March 11, 2019}}</ref> She successfully defended her title, winning via a head kick knockout in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/06/ufc-238-results-valentina-shevchenko-knockout-jessica-eye-highlight-reel-head-kick|title=UFC 238 results: Valentina Shevchenko knocks out Jessica Eye with head kick for the ages|date=June 9, 2019|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref> This win earned her the [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|''Performance of the Night'']] award.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/06/ufc-238-bonuses-tony-ferguson-cowboy-cerrone-valentina-shevchenko-henry-cejudo|title=UFC 238 bonuses: Tony Ferguson, 'Cowboy' Cerrone get a clear 'Fight of Night' winner|date=June 9, 2019|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShevchenko faced [[Liz Carmouche]] on August 10, 2019 at [[UFC on ESPN+ 14]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lowkickmma.com/valentina-shevchenko-will-defend-title-liz-carmouche/|title=Breaking: Valentina Shevchenko Will Defend Title Against Liz Carmouche In UFC Montevideo Main Event|author= Jon Fuentes|date=June 19, 2019|website=lowKickmma.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 19, 2019}}</ref> The pairing met previously under a regional promotion banner in 2010 with Carmouche winning the bout in the second round after the doctor stopped the bout due to a large cut stemming from an upkick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/27004239/sources-shevchenko-carmouche-rematch-set|title=Shevchenko-Carmouche rematch set|author=Brett Okamoto|date=June 18, 2019|publisher=espn.com|access-date=June 19, 2019}}</ref> Shevchenko won the rematch via unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2019/08/10/ufc-uruguay-results-valentina-shevchenko-dominates-liz-carmouche-win/|title=UFC Uruguay Results: Champion Valentina Shevchenko Dominates Liz Carmouche in Unanimous Decision Win|last=Harshman|first=Heath|date=August 10, 2019|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShevchenko defended her Flyweight title for the third time against [[Katlyn Chookagian]] on February 8, 2020 at [[UFC 247]].<ref name=\"Shevvs.Chook\">{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2019/11/valentina-shevchenko-vs-katlyn-chookagian-booked-ufc-title-fight-houston|title=Valentina Shevchenko set to defend UFC title vs. Katlyn Chookagian on Feb. 8|author=Staff|publisher=mmajunkie.com|access-date=November 26, 2019|date=November 21, 2019}}{{in lang|nl}}</ref> She won the fight via TKO in the third round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2020/02/09/ufc-247-results-valentina-shevchenko/|title=UFC 247 Results: Valentina Shevchenko Dominates Katlyn Chookagian|last=Evanoff|first=Josh|date=February 9, 2020|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShevchenko was scheduled to face [[Joanne Calderwood]] on June 6, 2020 to defend the [[UFC Women's Flyweight Championship]] at [[UFC 251]], but on March 31st, 2020, Shevchenko was forced to withdraw from the event due to a leg injury. <ref name=\"ShevchenkovsCalderwood\">{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/02/valentina-shevchenko-joanne-calderwood-flyweight-title-ufc-251-june|title=Champ Valentina Shevchenko meets Joanne Calderwood at UFC 251 in June|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=mmajunkie|author=Mike Bohn |access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Fighting style==\nA decorated kickboxer, Shevchenko is primarily known for precise counter-striking.<ref name=elbow>{{cite web|last=Connor |first=Ruebusch |url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2016/7/21/12243724/styles-make-flops-holly-holm-valentina-shevchenko-ufc-mma-technique-matchmaking-boring-fight-rousey |title=Styles Make Flops: Holly Holm vs Valentina Shevchenko and Strategic Matchmaking\n |publisher=BloodyElbow.com |date=July 21, 2016 |accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref> She is recognized for her exceptional ability to gauge the distance of an opponent's attack, then retaliate with a variety of counterattacks.<ref name=elbow/><ref name=flo>{{cite web|last=Duane |first=Finley |url=http://www.flocombat.com/article/51189-ufc-denver-pena-vs-shevchenko-breakdown |title=UFC Denver: Pena vs. Shevchenko Breakdown |publisher=FloCombat.com |date=January 27, 2017 |accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref> In a 2017 interview, Shevchenko noted the challenges of perfecting this technique in mixed martial arts: \"It's different to fight a wrestler and stand-up fighter. To feel the distance of her punch, it's different.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Lynch |first=James |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1h5zXuwqBXo |title=UFC 213's Valentina Shevchenko talks Amanda Nunes rematch |publisher=MMAOddsBreaker.com. |date=June 17, 2017 |accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter dodging an opponent's strike, Shevchenko will often counter with a fast right hook, a spinning wheel kick, or a spinning back fist. On offense, she makes regular use of forward right hooks and two-punch combinations. She also utilizes an outside leg kick, regularly thrown at the end of a flurry, or in the early stages of a round.<ref name=elbow/><ref name=flo/><ref>{{cite web|last=Richardson |first=Andrew |url=https://www.mmamania.com/2016/7/19/12207172/fighter-on-fighter-breaking-down-ufc-on-fox-20-valentina-shevchenko-chicago-mma |title=Fighter on Fighter: Breaking down UFC on FOX 20's Valentina Shevchenko |publisher=MMAMania.com |date=July 19, 2016 |accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her striking, Shevchenko is trained in grappling and has a black belt in Judo, as demonstrated by her multiple take-downs against Holly Holm, her armbar submission of Julianna Pe\u00f1a and her rear naked choke submission over Priscila Cachoeira.<ref name=Pena/><ref>{{cite web|last=Okamoto |first=Brett |url=http://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/17132150/valentina-shevchenko-upsets-holly-holm-decision |title=Shevchenko takes decision from Holm at UFC Chicago |publisher=ESPN.com |date=July 23, 2016 |accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n\n===Mixed martial arts===\n\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[UFC Women's Flyweight Championship|UFC Flyweight Championship]] (One time, current)\n***Three successful title defenses \n**[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]] (Three times) <small>vs. [[Julianna Pe\u00f1a]], [[Priscila Cachoeira]], and [[Jessica Eye]] </small><ref name=\"auto\" />.<ref name=\"Pena\" /><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n**Most [[List of UFC records#By division 5|wins in UFC Women's Flyweight division]] (5)\n**Most [[List of UFC records#By division 7|consecutive wins in UFC Women's Flyweight division]] (5)\n*'''[[MMAJunkie.com]]'''\n**2019 June Knockout of the Month <small>vs. [[Jessica Eye]]</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/07/knockout-of-the-month-june-2019-valentina-shevchenko-head-kick-jessica-eye-ufc-238|title=MMA Junkie's 'Knockout of the Month' for June: A crushing head kick by a champ|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Kickboxing===\n* [[Kunlun Fight#Kunlun Fight Women's Lightweight Championship|Kunlun Fight Women's Lightweight Championship]] (1 Title Defense)\n* 2014 [[Kunlun Fight#One Night Tournament Champions|Kunlun Fight Female -60kg Tournament Champion]]\n* 2013 World [[K-1]] Champion WKC, Peru [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2013 World [[K-1]] Champion WKC, Mexico [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2005 World Champion KF-1 MMA Pro, Korea, Seoul [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (57&nbsp;kg)\n* 2004 World Kickboxing Champion [[World Association of Kickboxing Organizations|WAKO]], Italy [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (56\u043ag)\n* 2003 World Champion KF-1 MMA Pro, Korea, Seoul [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (55&nbsp;kg)\n\n===Muay Thai===\n* 2015 I.F.M.A. Royal World cup Tournament Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2014 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2013 [[2013 World Combat Games|World Combat Games, Muay Thai Gold Medalist]] [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2012 [[World Muaythai Council#Female world champions|WMC Muaythai Female Super Lightweight World Champion]]<ref>{{cite news|title= Valentina Shevchenko|publisher= Awakening Fighters|date=|url= http://www.awakeningfighters.com/athletes/valentina-shevchenko/|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2011 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 2.png|Silver]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2010 [[2010 World Combat Games|World Combat Games, Muay Thai Gold Medalist]] [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2010 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (63.5&nbsp;kg)\n* 2009 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (60&nbsp;kg)\n* 2008 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (57&nbsp;kg)\n* 2007 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (57&nbsp;kg)\n* 2006 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (57&nbsp;kg)\n* 2006 World Muay Thai WMF Champion, Thailand [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] (57&nbsp;kg)\n* 2003 I.F.M.A. World Championship [[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] (57&nbsp;kg\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n|draws=\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=6\n|sub-wins=7\n|dec-wins=6\n|dq-wins=\n|other-wins=\n|ko-losses=1\n|sub-losses=\n|dec-losses=2\n|dq-losses=\n|other-losses=\n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|19\u20133\n|[[Katlyn Chookagian]]\n|TKO (elbows and punches)\n|[[UFC 247]] \n|{{dts